g.text: Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks at you as you remove the tape from the boombox. He doesn't say anything.
You: Keep the porta-reel at the harmless distance and wait.
You: Scratch that, I'm already crying. And I look dumb. And old.
Inland Empire: Garte. You have to convince Garte to let you sing karaoke in the Whirling. After you've won him over, you can *express* yourself. Let the pain out. Make everyone understand.
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": The porta-reel is just what you needed -- the reels attach to the apparatus with a satisfying click. The tape is routed behind the magnetic reader.
You: Nothing can stop me now.
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": You press the large button marked *Commencer* and the tape starts spinning. There's a small delay before the song starts playing...
Reaction Speed: A pawnshop -- a pawnshop would have a tape player...
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": There's no way to listen to the tape without a working tape player or porta-reel at hand.
Inland Empire: Crying is good, it gives your performance authenticity. Besides, you already know the lyrics since you've listened to it, like, a million times!
You: Could I sing this for karaoke? I think I could sing this.
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": A click -- then silence, for a bit. Then the tape stops spinning.
You: Press your ear against the speaker.
Encyclopedia: Yup. They're all here. All three verses.
Logic: Nothing to do with this right now.
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": Telling you about the tiniest church in Saint-Saëns, surrounded by even tinier yard. You almost feel the seaside mist on your skin. It's *mega* sad.
Inland Empire: But even just holding the tape makes you feel a little sad...
Inland Empire: Within seconds you know -- this is the one. The *real shit* you've been looking for. The one you trashed your room to. This one tells it like it is. This is your tune.
Within seconds you know -- this is the one. The *real shit* you've been looking for. The one you trashed your room to that Klaasje told you about. Perform it!
You: No, I couldn't! It's too sad, I might cry and trash the room again.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant watches you pack up the boombox. He doesn't say anything.
Inland Empire: *And* the B-side of the tape contains the instrumental version. It's like the world itself is telling you to do it. Only one obstacle stands on your way...
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": Then the organ starts playing a simple melancholic tune, echoing in the hallway. A lone singing voice joins in...
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": Immediately the boombox tunes itself back to the Friday night beats, vibrating on your shoulder.
"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": The porta-reel is just what you needed -- the reels attach to the apparatus with a satisfying click. The tape is routed behind the magnetic reader.
Inland Empire: Of course you could sing this! You could take sad to a whole new level with this. And you already know the lyrics since you've listened to it, like, a million times!

"Smallest Church in Saint-Saëns": It sounds like someone's moving in the room, getting comfortable. Then the organ starts playing a simple melancholic tune, echoing in the hallway. A lone singing voice joins in...
You: Not now. [Put the tape away.]
